<title>September 1995 Washington Watch Newsletter</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/wwatch/wwatch.gif"></center>
<p>
Volume 7<br>
Number 1<br>
October 27, 1995
<p><hr width=60% size=3><p>
<center><h2>CONTENTS</h2></center>
<font size=+1>
<ul><ul><ul><a href="#partial">Partial to Life</a><br>
<a href="#news">News Watch</a></font><br>
<ul type=ball><li><a href="#tax">Landmark Family Tax Relief</a><br>
<li><a href="#poll">FRC Poll: Wrong Track Woes</a><br>
</ul><font size=+1>
Court Watch</font><br>
<ul type=ball><li><a href="#colorado">Colorado's Rocky Day in Court</a><br>
</ul><font size=+1>
Policy Update</font><br>
<ul type=ball><li><a href="#kinsey">Kinsey Mystery: 50 Years and Tottering</a><br>
</ul><font size=+1>
<a href="#board">Bulletin Board</a><br>
Inside D.C.</font><br>
<ul type=ball><li><a href="#tv">FRC's "Straight Talk" Takes Flight</a><br>
</ul><font size=+1>
Special Report: Lobbying Reform</font><br>
<ul type=ball><li><a href="#lobby">Lobbyists: No Apples for McIntosh</a><br>
</ul><font size=+1>
<a href="#horizon">On the Horizon</a><br>
</ul></ul></ul></font>
<center><font size=-1><b>Bulleted items are this month's highlighted issues</b>
</font></center>
<p><hr size=5 noshade><p>
<a name="partial"><center><h1>Partial to Life</h1></center>
<p>
<font size=+3>D</font>uring his recent visit to the U.S., Pope John Paul II 
spoke movingly of how America's founding documents and the abolition 
of slavery are linked with the moral causes of today.  &quot;President
Lincoln's question is no less a question for the present generation
of Americans,&quot; the pope said in Baltimore.  &quot;Democracy cannot 
be sustained without a shared commitment to certain moral truths
about the human person and human community.&quot;
<p>
As slavery was in the years before the Civil War, abortion is
a defining moral question.  The issue &quot;that will not go away&quot; 
is once again on the front burner of public debate.  Interestingly enough,
while talk grows among some leading conservatives about the circumstances
under which they could endorse &quot;pro-choice&quot; politicians, several 
leading liberal publications are giving space to the weightiest arguments 
against abortion on demand.
<p>
<center><h3>Facing Reality</h3></center>
<p>
The cover story in September's <i>Atlantic Monthly</i> is devoted to
abortion.  Prof. George McKenna of the City College of New York writes 
of the inescapable parallels between the pro-slavery and 
pro-abortion movements, including their rhetoric of &quot;privacy,&quot;
&quot;choice,&quot; and the insistence that &quot;religion&quot; should 
not interfere in the controversy. McKenna argues that abortion opponents
should adopt a &quot;Lincolnian&quot; position designed not to
outlaw abortion immediately through legislation, but to restrict it while 
galvanizing public opinion against the practice.
<p>
Naomi Wolf, an avowed feminist, writes in an Oct. 16 <i>New Republic</i>
article entitled &quot;Our Bodies, Our Souls&quot; that the feminist 
movement errs when it fails to acknowledge that abortion is an 
&quot;evil,&quot; that it kills &quot;children&quot; and traumatizes many 
women. While Wolf does not abandon her &quot;pro-choice&quot; position, 
she does urge defenders of abortion to embrace a &quot;moral framework&quot; 
that mourns the loss of the aborted child.
<p>
To these ripples must be added the wave caused by the partial
conversion of Norma McCorvey to the anti-abortion cause.  McCorvey, 
the &quot;Jane Roe&quot; of <i>Roe v. Wade</i>, recently abandoned the
pro-abortion camp and was baptized a Christian.  In an interview
on <i>ABC News</i>, she cited the grief that overwhelmed her when she 
saw &quot;empty swings&quot; in a park and thought of the children
whose deaths by abortion she had helped to cause.
<p><hr width=45% size=2><p>
<center><i><font size=+2>"ABORTION IS A DEFINING<br>
MORAL QUESTION . . ."</font></i></center>
<p><hr width=45% size=2><p>
<center><h3>Taking Action</h3></center>
<p>
While the public debate takes new turns, Congress has begun to
take forthright action to restrict abortion.  The House of 
Representatives voted in August to ensure that no federal health monies
would be denied to medical schools that refuse to abide by the
new abortion training mandate from the Accreditation Council for 
Graduate Medical Education. The House also reinstated a
stronger version of the Hyde Amendment limiting federal abortion
funding.  Both of these amendments, plus a ban on federally supported 
human embryo research, were attached to the 1996 Labor, Health and 
Human Services appropriation bill.
<p>
Perhaps the most important measure right now is the Partial Birth
Abortion Ban Act (H.R. 1833), cosponsored by 152 members of Congress, 
including 25 Democrats. A &quot;partial birth&quot; abortion is
a technique used to kill babies in the second or third trimester.
 It involves deliberately breech-delivering the baby alive until only 
his/her head remains in the mother's uterus while the rest of the
body protrudes into the birth canal.  The abortionist then jabs
surgical scissors into the base of the
baby's skull, opens the scissors to widen the cavity, then uses
a vacuum catheter to suction out the
brain.  Delivery of the now-dead baby with its collapsed skull
completes the procedure. A vote in the full House -- an historic 
moment in the rejuvenated national abortion debate -- is imminent.
<p>
<center><h3>What You Can Do</h3></center>
<p>
Time is short.  Call 202-225-3121.  Urge your representative to
vote for H.R. 1833, the Partial Birth Abortion Ban Act.  At the same 
time, urge him or her to stand fast for the pro-life House
positions in the 1996 Labor, Health, and Human Services bill.
<p><hr><p>
<a name="news">
<center><h2><font size=+3>N</font>EWS <font size=+3>W</font>ATCH</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>On the Hill</h3>
<p><a name="tax>
<b>Families First.</b>  The long struggle to provide tax relief for America's
families took a big step forward as the Senate Finance Committee approved 
a permanent $500 per-child tax credit on Oct. 19.  Marriage penalty relief, 
expanded individual retirement accounts (IRAs), and adoption tax
credits were also included.  Since the House has already approved
an even larger tax relief package with similar provisions, it appears that 
Congress will soon put family tax relief on the President's desk.  White 
House officials continue to threaten a Presidential veto.
<p>
<b>Careering.</b>  Hasty politicking on job training bills has both houses
talking dollars but not sense. The Careers Bill (H.R. 1617) and the 
Workforce Development Act (S. 143) streamline federal job
training programs but fail to uproot elements of Goals 2000 and
the School-to-Work initiative, with its central economic planning features. 
Congressmen are playing right into this agenda by
mandating data collection for a vast Labor Market Information
System, and promoting the National Skill Standards Board.  H.R. 1617 and 
S. 143 passed in their respective houses and passage in some form now 
seems certain.
<p>
<b>Back from the Brink.</b>  According to the 1995 Trustees Report, Medicare
will be bankrupt by the year 2002 unless major reforms are enacted.  
The full House approved reforms on Oct. 19 which 
introduce competition and choice into the failing Medicare system.
 In addition to capping the growth in Medicare spending, Medisave 
accounts for seniors -- similar to those proposed for
working families in Rep. Bill Archer's (R-Tex.) H.R. 1818 -- would
be established.  These accounts would allow seniors to choose their 
own doctors and pay for services not covered by a
traditional insurance plan (i.e., prescription drugs or long-term
care premiums).
<p>
<center><h3>Around Town</h3></center>
<p>
<b>Red-blooded Change.</b>  For years, the American Red Cross has produced
AIDS materials full of misinformation.  Condoms have been emphasized 
instead of behavioral change.  Recently, however, Red Cross officials 
reversed course, calling for abstinence, HIV testing, partner notification,
and discouragement of  illegal behavior.  The largest federally-funded
AIDS education group, Red Cross still has a ways to go, however, since 
it still uses a &quot;nonjudgmental approach to HIV/AIDS 
education&quot; for youth, omitting the terms &quot;husbands&quot;
and &quot;wives&quot; in favor of  &quot;partners&quot; and
portraying homosexuality as no different from heterosexuality.
<p>
<b>Teen Trends.</b> New studies from the Centers for Disease Control
(CDC) find that: 1) births to teenage mothers declined by 4 percent 
from 1991-1993; 2) teen pregnancy rates (including both
births and abortions) were down in a majority of states; and 3)
after 50 years of increases, birth
rates among unwed women of all ages have leveled off for three
years at 45.3 per 1,000 unmarried women.  These encouraging figures 
coincide with an increase in both abstinent teenagers and in states 
adopting legislation encouraging abstinence education.
<p>
<center><h3>Across the Nation</h3></center>
<p>
<b>Out of Control.</b> The large volume of calls from indignant parents
and teachers to the National Education Association (NEA) indicate the union 
went too far when it decided to promote the 
&quot;celebration of a Lesbian and Gay History Month&quot; endorsed
by homosexual groups and the American Historical Association.  At 
least one of the groups promoting the October observance
seems ready to admit defeat.  The president of the Gay, Lesbian,
and Straight Teachers Network told an <i>Education Week</i> reporter 
that the conservative reaction was &quot;beyond our control.&quot; 
<p>
<b>Capping Debate.</b> When members of the House and Senate meet soon
to strike agreements on a welfare reform bill, the defining issue will 
be the family cap. If passed, the cap would deny a
federally-funded increase in cash benefits to mothers who bear
additional children while on welfare.  While modest in scope, the 
cap is a critical first step in a larger effort to renew personal
responsibility.  Massachusetts recently went further by introducing
the first legislation in the nation that would terminate cash payments 
to unwed teenage mothers.
<p><a name="poll">
<b>FRC Survey.</b>  FRC's fourth annual Family Issues Survey, to be released
in late November, shows that most Americans (66 percent) believe &quot;things 
have pretty seriously gotten off on the wrong track&quot; -- compared 
to 21 percent who feel that things in America are on the
&quot;right track.&quot;  High &quot;wrong-track&quot;
perceptions usually reflect economic problems, and, indeed, a
new Census Bureau study shows that middle-class incomes showed no 
gains last year.  Earnings for full-time workers actually
dropped.  However, FRC's poll also shows that the majority (61
percent) of those who think the country is on the wrong track cite 
&quot;the breakdown of the family and a decline in values&quot; rather
than U.S. economic problems.
<p>
<center><h3>Permission to Copy</h3></center>
<p>
This newsletter, or any portion thereof, may be reproduced, without
alteration, for non-commercial purposes without prior permission from 
Family Research Council. Please contact the address below for permission 
regarding all other uses.
<p><hr><p>
<a name="colorado">
<center><h2><font size=+3>C</font>OURT <font size=+3>W</font>ATCH</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>Colorado Ambush?</h3>
<p>
Oral argument was held Oct. 10 in the U.S. Supreme Court over
Colorado's Amendment Two.  A decision is expected in early spring.  At 
issue is the voter-approved referendum amending Colorado's state 
constitution so that homosexuals do not qualify for special rights. 
The measure invalidates special homosexual rights laws in several cities,
including Aspen, Boulder and Denver, but was struck down by Colorado's 
liberal state supreme court.
<p>
Amendment Two was initiated by Coloradans who perceived that homosexual
rights laws threaten their freedoms of religion, association and speech, 
as well as economic liberties.  For example, Boy Scout programs have 
been attacked in many places where &quot;gay rights&quot; laws are in
effect.
<p>
If the tone of the questioning by justices was any indication,
the Amendment could be in for a rough ride.  Led by Clinton appointees 
Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen Breyer, six justices asked questions 
that seemed hostile.  Only Justice Antonin Scalia vigorously defended 
the law, arguing that the people of Colorado do not discriminate merely
by approving limits on special rights for particular groups -- 
particularly those which are not bona fide minorities. Scalia noted
that many states prohibit bigamy and homosexual conduct.  If these
laws are constitutional, he asked, then why can't Colorado bar special 
status for sexual orientation?
<p>
Justice Ginsburg answered that Colorado repealed sodomy laws in
1972, and that passage of the Amendment constituted a denial of 
homosexuals' access to the political process.  Scalia said,
however, that if that logic is applied, then all groups disadvantaged
by state laws, including smokers, have suffered unconstitutional 
discrimination.
<p>
Oral arguments do not dictate how a case will be decided, but
the hearing showed just how liberal the court remains in some crucial areas. 
Family Research Council filed a &quot;friend of the court&quot;
brief warning that delicate matters are best resolved through
laws that reflect bedrock cultural values.  Drafted by attorney 
Melissa Wells-Petry, who has written widely in support of the
military's ban on homosexuals, the brief warns that a reversal
of Amendment Two would constitute as large and destructive a judicial 
power grab as occurred in <i>Roe v. Wade</i> (1973).
<p><hr><p>
<a name="kinsey">
<center><h2><font size=+3>P</font>OLICY <font size=+3>U</font>PDATE</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>Kinsey Breakthrough</h3>
<p>
Answering charges raised by FRC's new video, <i>The Children of 
Table 34</i>, Kinsey Institute Director John Bancroft told the 
<i>Indianapolis Star</i> (Sept. 19) that he believes the child sex data 
in the famous Kinsey Report from the 1940s was the work of one pedophile.
This account contradicts that of Alfred C. Kinsey himself, who wrote in 
<i>Sexual Behavior in the Human Male</i> (1948) that explicit sexual 
data on 317 youngsters was collected by nine pedophiles.
<p>
Kinsey's findings continue to be the most influential data on
sex research published in this century.  Because the data have been 
used to validate the idea of child sexuality that animates most of
sexology and today's sex education, public illumination of Kinsey's
ethical swamp may lead to educational, legal and scientific reform. 
FRC is pressing Congress for an investigation into the
Kinsey Institute's child sexuality files, whose existence Dr.
Bancroft has now confirmed.  First
questions:  Who was the aforementioned pedophile and how did he
get access to hundreds of children, including infants?  Dr. Judith 
Reisman, who first explored the Kinsey child data in a 1981 monograph, 
and later in the 1990 book <i>Kinsey, Sex and Fraud</i>
with co-author Edward Eichel and editors Dr. J. Gordon Muir and Dr. 
John H. Court, says she is encouraged that the 50-year-old mystery 
might finally be solved.
<P>
Meanwhile, FRC is appealing the Public Broadcasting Service's
rejection of <i>The Children of Table 34</i> for airing. PBS 
designates June as Gay Pride Month and, in mid-October, began 
running a four-part series celebrating homosexual activism.  This
same PBS says that the FRC video presents a &quot;conflict&quot; 
because FRC, as a pro-family group, has an interest in the material. 
Presumably, the &quot;conflict&quot; is that the film accords with
FRC's stated aim of protecting children from sexual abuse.
<p>
The Kinsey Institute is still a heavy recipient of taxpayer money
through its connection with Indiana University.  Kinsey's work and 
continuing influence are long overdue for public scrutiny.
<p><hr><p>
