<title>WITH LIBERTY AND JUSTICE FOR ALL</title>

<body>

<center>

<img src="/townhall/FRC/fampol/fampolgn.gif">

<h1>With Liberty and Justice for All</h1>
<h2><i>Redefining the Educational Choice Debate</i></h2>

</center>

<p>

<font size=+3>E</font>ducation is a so-called mixed good. It offers both 
public and private benefits. Thus, the debate over education policy in 
America is often cast as a clash between public and private interests,
a conflict between equity and liberty. In the words of social
scientist James Coleman:

<p><blockquote>

<i>[C]ontradictions . . . arise out of two simultaneously-held values
that are very relevant to most Americans. The first is the autonomy
and choice of parents to do all they can to raise their children
to adulthood. The second is the value we place on having a society
that is not fragmented by divisions imposed by segregated or exclusive
upbringing.</i>[1]

</blockquote><p>

Liberty and equity are not mutually-exclusive concepts. But if
their proper relationship is to be achieved, policymakers must
develop a new understanding of equal opportunity based on liberty.
Education policy in America today often fails to pay respect to
the need for parents to direct their children's upbringing. Indeed,
calls for parental choice in education typically run headlong
into the myth of the &quot;common school&quot; and the rhetoric
of &quot;equal opportunity&quot; -- outmoded ideas which the education
establishment successfully employs to protect its vested interest.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Paine believed that most poor<br>
parents were well aware of the<br>
benefits of education and that<br>
heavy taxation was the chief<br>
cause of their under-investment<br>
in education.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

Thus, a gradual &quot;demythologizing&quot; of the common school
as the bulwark of democracy and the ultimate expression of equal
opportunity will be necessary to sustain any hope of expanding
private liberty (and improving student performance) through parental
choice in education. Otherwise, the political power of the teacher
unions and the philosophical tensions inherent in education will
continue to render choice an elusive goal.

<p>

<center><h3>No Paine, No Gain</h3></center>

<p>

Political theorists have long debated whether government should
be involved in education in any capacity. More than two centuries
ago, Thomas Jefferson made an eloquent case for a state role in
education in a letter to George Wythe:

<p><blockquote>

<i>Preach, my dear Sir, a crusade against ignorance, establish and
improve the law for educating the common people. Let our countrymen
know that the people alone can protect us against these evils,
and that the tax which will be paid for this purpose is not more
than the thousandth part of what will be paid to kings, priests
and nobles who will rise up among us if we leave the people in
ignorance.</i>[2]

</blockquote><p>

Interestingly, many of the classical economists who were busy
ardently defending laissez-faire economic policies in Jefferson's
day were also forceful advocates of a state role in education.
Adam Smith argued in <I>The Wealth of Nations</I> that the market
would fail to capture the social benefits of education because
of the divergence between public and private interests.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Mill's sympathy for government<br>
paternalism did not extend to<br>
justifying inefficient and<br>
inferior education in the name<br>
of broad public purposes.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

But Smith stopped short of issuing an unqualified endorsement
of state-sponsored education. Contrasting the quality of education
under public and private arrangement, Smith argued that private
schools were more successful in cultivating skills in reading,
writing and arithmetic.[3] While eager to promote the education of
all students, Smith did not share the conviction of Jeremy Bentham
and other utilitarians that government could successfully administer
education. Instead, he argued for a wide dispersal of educational
expenditure and decision-making to prevent teacher compensation
from being made independent of effort.

<p>

Similarly, Thomas Paine believed that most poor parents were well
aware of the benefits of education and that heavy taxation was
the chief cause of their underinvestment in education. Paine proposed
a much more far-reaching decentralization of authority that would
further increase parental freedom of choice and competition among
schools. In <I>The Rights of Man</I>, he proposed &quot;to make
a remission of taxes to every poor family out of the surplus taxes
. . . enjoining the parents of such children to send them to 
school.&quot;[4]

<p>

John Stuart Mill's writings on the question of state education
are ambiguous and at times self-contradictory because he, too,
was acutely aware of the tension between personal liberty and
the public purposes of education. On the one hand, Mill differed
from Paine. Mill believed that government must control education
because parents were incompetent to judge their children's best
interests. But in a moment of supreme doubt, he wrote: &quot;A
general State education is a mere contrivance for moulding [sic]
people to be exactly like one another. . . it establishes a despotism
over the mind.&quot;[5] Mill's enthusiasm for state schools, moreover,
depended on the assumption that the public schools would always
be superior to private institutions. He wrote in <I>On Liberty</I>
that a state school should exist, &quot;if it exist at all, as
one among many competing experiments, carried on for the purpose
of example and stimulus, to keep the others up to a certain standard
of excellence.&quot;[6] Mill's sympathy for government paternalism
did not extend to justifying inefficient and inferior education
in the name of broad public purposes.

<p>

In the earliest years of the Republic, parental fees provided
the majority of funding for schools, as Adam Smith and Thomas
Paine had recommended. As parents exercised their freedom to determine
the shape of their children's education, the great heterogeneity
of the nation expressed itself in the diversity and autonomy of
its local schools.

<p>

Nineteenth century reformers, however, launched a campaign to
redefine education as the means to restore morality, justice and
social conformity. A public-purpose rationale began to triumph
over respect for the private benefits afforded parents by the
freedom and genuine diversity in the schools. Under Horace Mann's
leadership, reformers succeeded in creating a system that was
&quot;bureaucratic and professional, designed to ensure, so the
story goes, that education would be taken out of politics and
placed in the hands of impartial experts devoted to the public
interest.&quot; It was the &quot;one best system,&quot; also referred
to as the &quot;common school.&quot;[7]

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Over the last three decades,<br>
it has become increasingly<br>
evident that the public school<br>
is failing to fulfill its high-<br>
minded egalitarian purpose.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

Egalitarian democracy was now operationally-defined as centrally-planned
uniformity, secured through bureaucratic arrangements. According
to education historian E.G. West, however, it was teachers and
government officials, not discontented parents, who brought about
the change.[8] And, as economist Milton Friedman has observed, it
was hardly an apolitical enterprise: &quot;Though the arguments
were all pitched in terms of the public interest, much of the
support of teachers and administrators for the public school movement
derived from a narrow self-interest,&quot; including greater control
over the schools and almost guaranteed salaries now that government
was the paymaster.[9] Friedman notes that reformers simply capitalized
on public sympathy for the concept of equal opportunity to succeed
in establishing universal, &quot;free&quot; and compulsory education.[10]
That same egalitarian impulse had already found private expression
in the form of charity schools and the adjustment of school fees
according to means, as West and other historians report.[11]

<p>

<center><h3>From Equity to Liberty</h3></center>

<p>

Over the last three decades, it has become increasingly evident
that the public school is failing to fulfill its high-minded egalitarian
purpose. Equity &quot;based on homogeneity has occurred only by
discriminating against some, segregating others, and denying the
possibilities of alternative ways of life.&quot;[12] Historian David
Cohen explains:

<p><blockquote>

<i>Education has long been seen as both the chief antidote to
poverty and the principal means for assimilating ethnic and racial
minorities. . . . Since [the late 1960s], however, events have
cast serious doubt on these two venerable articles of faith .
. . that education is the high road to equality or social 
integration.</i>[13]

</blockquote><p>

In 1966, Coleman released his now-famous Equality of Educational
Opportunity report, concluding that differences in the quality
of the nation's schools bear only a trivial relationship to differences
in the educational achievement of the nation's students. Coleman's
report posed a fundamental question: If schools have little effect
on differences in children's achievement, is state-controlled
public education the key to social justice?

<p>

At about the same time, empirical evidence of low academic performance
in the public schools caused Friedman to start repopularizing
criticisms of the &quot;common school&quot; first made by Smith,
Paine, and Mill. As an alternative, Friedman began calling for
educational vouchers that would give parents freedom of choice,
thereby increasing competitive supply. Given the ineffectiveness
of the present education system, he asked rhetorically, &quot;Wherein
are the 'neighborhood effects' that justify such use of tax 
money?&quot;[14]

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Coleman's report posed a<br>
fundamental question: If<br>
schools have little effect<br>
on differences in children's<br>
achievement, is state-<br>
controlled public education<br>
the key to social justice?
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

To broaden the base of potential support for vouchers, Friedman
took pains to argue that his proposal would actually enhance equality
of opportunity. Under the current system, he noted, wealthy families
have significantly more freedom of choice than low-income families.
Poor families are trapped in poor school districts. They lack
the resources to move or to choose private schools. &quot;Under
present arrangements, stratification of residential areas effectively
restricts the intermingling of children from decidedly different
backgrounds. . . . Our present system, far from equalizing opportunity,
very likely does the opposite.&quot;[15]

<p>

While Friedman questioned the practical interpretation of the
public purposes of education, he appealed primarily to a philosophical
commitment to individual liberty. &quot;Persuasive as [the] argument
[for achieving a common core of values] is, . . . [o]n grounds
of principle, it conflicts with the preservation of freedom itself,&quot;
he wrote.[16] Friedman suggested that the circumstances that justified
the definition of education as a predominantly public good in
the Progressive Era were eclipsed by circumstances that now favor
the definition of education as a private good.

<p>

While vouchers appealed to Friedman as a means to introduce the
efficiency of the market into education, liberal social analyst
Christopher Jencks embraced vouchers as a means to equalize opportunity
by improving the education of low-income and minority children.
Favoring egalitarian over libertarian goals, he designed a voucher
experiment for the Office of Economic Opportunity (OEO) in the
1960s that included heavy regulatory burdens governing admissions
policies, fiscal incentives for schools to accept poor students,
and the creation of an educational voucher agency to oversee the
program. The OEO voucher experiment demonstrated the problems
of policy design and political opposition that would hamper implementation
of educational choice even after changing philosophical definitions
had begun to broaden its appeal.

<p>

In most of the prospective test sites, local educators and grass-roots
organizations blocked Jencks' proposal. &quot;In effect, there
was no constituency for a plan that threatened the job security
of teachers [and] compromised the independence of private schools.&quot;[17]
Finally, the Alum Rock school district in California agreed to
the voucher demonstration; but, &quot;the process of negotiation
between federal sponsors and local interest groups resulted in
a dramatic alteration of the voucher plan. Ultimately, no private
schools participated . . . [and] [n]o teachers in unpopular programs
lost their jobs. In fact, none of the incentives usually thought
to spur initiative in the private sector were present in Alum
Rock.&quot;[18] Interestingly, Jencks and his associates concluded
that, &quot;if restrictions are too rigid, a voucher system is
likely to be indistinguishable from the present public school
system.&quot;[19] Conservatives argued that the regulations Jencks
himself proposed to satisfy equity requirements emasculated the
voucher concept, precluding an adequate test of educational choice.

<p>

The unregulated character of Friedman's proposals, however, still
posed too great a risk to liberal policymakers to win passage.
Writing at the time, education analyst Dennis Doyle observed:

<p><blockquote>

<i>The basic reason that policymakers will not support either
Jencks or Friedman vouchers is that the dimension of vouchers
that makes them interesting -- choice -- still threatens an egalitarian
society. At the present time only one important interest group
might change this, and that group is minorities in general, especially
[black Americans]. . . . [T]here is a growing body of minority
and black opinion which holds that choice itself is the key to
equality -- and that without choice, equal educational opportunity
will remain unfulfilled.</i>[20]

</blockquote><p>

Alum Rock proved to be an early sign of increasing national interest
in the concept of educational choice -- coupled with persistently
dubious prospects for political passage of any far-reaching voucher
proposal.

<p>

<center><h3>Toward a Philosophical Redefinition</h3></center>

<p>

As the limitations of the common school have grown increasingly
obvious and the case for educational choice more plausible, choice
opponents have clung more desperately to the &quot;myth of the
common school&quot; as a pluralist and apolitical institution.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Under the current system<br>
wealthy families have<br>
significantly more freedom<br>
of choice than low-income<br>
families trapped in poor<br>
school districts.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

From the outset, a primary objective of the common school was
the socialization of all children in an overtly religious, yet
non-sectarian environment. Educator Charles Glenn's book <I>The
Myth of the Common School</I> portrays the movement toward state
education as a mission to acculturate immigrants into the predominantly
Protestant culture of 19th-century America. The religion of the
early common school was a least-common-denominator Christianity
tending toward the Unitarianism of the schools' founding fathers.
Central Protestant doctrines like sin, and salvation by faith
in Christ were expunged as committee review of curriculum and
teaching took hold, implanting a more muted religion of good and
evil, along with a hefty dose of strictly civic morality. Catholics,
Jews, and Lutherans, often the alien target of the common school
movement, found their beliefs discouraged and discounted as 
&quot;sectarian&quot; in the new schools. So began the tradition of 
&quot;publicly-sponsored orthodoxy,&quot; as long-time education observer 
Stephen Arons calls it, in which the government defines through the 
public schools a set of &quot;normative&quot; values and beliefs.[21]

<p>

But even genuine efforts to find common ground are of little avail,
for education is the very enterprise of discovering and defending
first principles. It cannot be replaced by some &quot;value-neutral&quot;
process. As Aristotle said, education is about teaching the young
to lead the good life. Since men disagree about what the good
life is, men disagree about education. Glenn muses that &quot;we
may have set ourselves an impossible task in seeking to provide
a single model of education that is to be at once capable of nurturing
character and civic virtue and yet inoffensive to the conviction
of any parent.&quot;[22] Reformers eager to employ the common school
as an agent of social change offend parents' beliefs all the more.

<p>

The socialization mission is a flat violation of families' First
Amendment freedoms of belief and expression, argues Arons. The
First Amendment, he believes, not only protects parents' freedom
to express their beliefs, but also to pass on those beliefs to
their children.[23] Yet, compulsory public education forces parents
to surrender these tender matters of conscience to the political
majority. Aron continues, &quot;The level of coercion required
to resolve these value conflicts would be inconsistent with personal
liberty and political democracy.&quot;[24] While some argue that private
schools provide an adequate escape hatch from the public schools,
Arons argues that requiring parents to purchase their First Amendment
freedoms is as crass as taxing voters to enter the polls.

<p>

Thus, he concludes: &quot;[T]he present structure of public education
is unconstitutional because the primary victims of the unequal
distribution of liberty are the poor, working people and racial
minorities.&quot;[25] The comment reflects a subtle but critically
important reframing of the equity debate. By defining equity as
more nearly an &quot;equality of liberty,&quot; Arons offers a
fledgling strategy to help temper sharp oscillations between liberty
and equity, or private and public purposes, in education.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Circumstances that justified<br>
the definition of education<br>
as a predominantly public<br>
good in the Progressive era<br>
have been eclipsed by<br>
circumstances that now<br>
favor the definition of<br>
education as a predominantly<br>
private good.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

But Arons also casts specific doubt on the priority of the public
benefits of education: &quot;The legitimacy of the political consensus,
however weak, may be eliminated by government interference in
the process of belief and value formation.&quot;[26] Arons' searching
concern echoes the early 20th-century cautions of Princeton theologian
J. Gresham Machen that monopolistic state education would be &quot;the
most effective engine of tyranny and intellectual stagnation that
has yet been devised.&quot;[27] Machen argued that only competition
with private schools would keep the state schools healthy and
thus admonished a group of Christian school educators, &quot;May
the distinctiveness of your Christian schools never be lost; may
it never give place, by a false 'Americanization,' to a drab uniformity
which is the most un-American thing that could possibly be 
conceived!&quot;[28]

<p>

If coercion on matters of conscience results in further splintering
of communities, Arons seems to suggest government monopoly of
education may negate its public benefits altogether.

<p>

<center><h3>Are Vouchers the Right Mechanism?</h3></center>

<p>

If the argument for parental choice in education is based on the
philosophy of freedom from coercion, then the mechanism for choice
cannot be permitted to increase state coercion of parents or the
private sector.

<p>

Funding and regulation are the two defining characteristics of
public agencies, nearly always appearing hand in hand. The unhappy
results are dramatically evident in Canada, where some provinces'
religious and private schools are a part of the public school
system and receive state funding. Today many religious schools
depend heavily on subsidies from the Canadian government and have
subsequently lost their defining character.[29]

<p>

While voucher proponents originally made little distinction, today
they are careful to specify that voucher payments must flow directly
to parents or students -- not to private institutions. First Amendment
attorney William Bentley Ball argues that such precision is necessary
to sidestep potential entanglement problems.[30]

<p>

Nevertheless, many perceive the difference between aid to religious
institutions and aid to individuals to be only semantic and believe
vouchers do pose a threat to religious schools.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Genuine efforts to find common<br>
ground are of little avail, for<br>
education is the very enterprise<br>
of discovering and defending<br>
first principles. Aristotle said<br>
education is about teaching the<br>
young to lead the good life.<br>
Since men disagree about what<br>
the good life is, men disagree<br>
about education.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

The threat of future tinkering with the language of such laws
should not be dismissed, according to education researcher Chester
Finn. &quot;Some [private schools] to be sure, like to think they...can
obtain aid without saddling themselves with unacceptable forms
of regulation. But most...are more or less resigned to amalgamating
or choosing between assistance and autonomy.&quot;[31]

<p>

In the current federal political landscape, the compromises necessary
to achieve a winning voucher proposal come at too dear a price
for many would-be supporters. In the recent debate over vouchers
for the District of Columbia, the political payoff for the key
support of centrist Sen. Jim Jeffords (R-Vt.) was the surrender
of the basic principle for which every true religious school exists:
the fusion of faith and learning. Jeffords demanded and won the
addition of two provisions regarding religion. The first established
a religious opt-in provision requiring written consent from parents
for students to participate in religious courses or activities.
The second was even more worrisome to friends of religious liberty,
mandating that no school could use the voucher money to pay for
its religious courses or activities. Given such provisions, James
Cardinal Hickey made it clear that schools of the Archiocese of
Washington, D.C. would not participate in the voucher program.
With Catholic schools totalling some 80 percent of the private
schools in the city, the D.C. voucher scenario was nearly a re-run
of Alum Rock.

<p>

<center><h3>Concerns Specific to Means-Tested Vouchers</h3></center>

<p>

Means-tested vouchers, in particular, suffer from several potentially
fatal flaws. Assessing social reforms in the 1970s, Irving Kristol
comments that &quot;[p]ractically all social reforms 'work' in
that they do distribute some benefits to the people whom they
aim to help.&quot;[32] Means-tested vouchers would very likely 
&quot;work&quot; to improve the educational prospects of a few low-income 
children -- perhaps even helping to mold the next Clarence Thomas. Kristol
quickly notes, however, that there are two problems inherent in
giving money only to the poor.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Today many religious schools in<br>
Canada have come to depend heavily<br>
on subsidies from the government<br>
and have subsequently lost their<br>
defining character.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

The primary difficulty is that means-tested benefits always establish
a huge disincentive for families on the margin to escape the poverty
trap.

<p>

Moreover, Kristol argues that means-tested benefits do a
grave disservice to a society by establishing an arbitrary definition
of &quot;poor.&quot;

<p>

Social reform, in other words, should actively seek to minimize
class conflict by advancing low- and middle-income interests in
tandem. A recent column by William Raspberry of <I>The Washington
Post</I> confirms the perspicacity of Kristol's insight. &quot;The
recent political trend,&quot; Raspberry observes, &quot;is to
legislate luck for entire classes of people. Some get the breaks,
and some get suckered. . . .It isn't that Americans no longer
care about the common good, but that they have lost faith in mutuality.
They're afraid of being played for suckers.&quot;[33]

<p>

Both survey and anecdotal evidence suggest that school voucher
proposals may indeed be falling prey to class resentment over
policies that tax Reagan voters to bestow benefits on Clinton
backers. In the wake of the school choice defeat in California,
pollster Frank Luntz found that seven out of 10 Californians said
they do not favor exclusive targeting of lower-income students.
On the other hand, two-thirds of all California voters said that
they would be willing to support choice in education in the future
if it did not cost any additional tax money.[34]

<p>

Gene Piccolo of the Choice in Education League in Minnesota reports
voter concern over the potential of the pending voucher initiative
in his state to create a new entitlement. He also reports a subtle
but distinctive undertone of middle-class suburbanite resentment
among voucher opponents -- perhaps, he believes, because Minnesota
already boasts one of the highest levels of public welfare spending
in the country.

<p>

&quot;Publicly-funded compassion fatigue&quot; may render means-tested
vouchers a political non-starter in other parts of the country
as well. The success of the privately- funded voucher (or scholarship)
movement, by contrast, suggests that Americans are beginning to
draw a sharp distinction between &quot;compassion&quot; and government
solutions -- and between &quot;compassion&quot; and equality in
the egalitarian sense.

<p>

<center><h3>A New Look at Tax Credits</h3></center>

<p>

Given the failure to establish a full educational choice program
anywhere in the U.S. after nearly a quarter century, choice proponents
must challenge themselves to develop a new scheme. The proposal
should place a premium on liberty and on the private benefits
of education while reformulating the public-purpose rhetoric employed
by the education establishment. A new proposal should also avoid
the weaknesses associated with vouchers, including the menace
of government regulation, consistent challenges to their constitutionality,
dim prospects for political passage, the danger of expanding an
entitlement mentality and a narrow coalition of beneficiaries
to support passage. A refundable tax credit scheme is more likely
to overleap these hurdles than means-tested voucher demonstration
projects.

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Means-tested benefits always<br>
establish a huge disincentive<br>
for families on the margin to<br>
escape the poverty trap.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

The more universal the private benefits, the more likely the U.S.
Supreme Court will be to uphold the proposal. In the 1983 case
<I>Mueller v. Allen</I>, the court held that a program &quot;that
neutrally provides state assistance to a broad spectrum of citizens
is not readily subject to challenge under the Establishment 
Clause.&quot;[35] The program in question was a Minnesota tax deduction 
for tuition, transportation and textbooks, which had been broadly defined 
to include extra educational benefits for even public school students.

<p>

However, by defining &quot;allowable uses&quot; or &quot;eligible
institutions,&quot; tax benefits linked to tuition may carry the
same threat of regulation as vouchers. Or they might exclude religious
institutions altogether. But a refundable tax credit for the &quot;non-use
of the public school&quot; would avoid such meddling, eliminating
the need to define allowable uses of the tax credit. Since 
&quot;non-users&quot; of the public schools already exist, there would be 
no further need to define or regulate recipients. Recently proposed in 
Idaho, the tax credit for the non-use of the public school received a
favorable review from the state attorney general, who cited it
as fundamentally different from both the tuition tax credits and
the vouchers which the state's strict definition of separation
of church and state would prohibit. &quot;[T]he proposed initiative's
grant of the tax credit to parents of all non-public school students
-- home-schooled, private non-sectarian, and private parochial
-- coupled with the absence of a direct financial benefit to parochial
schools, makes it probable this proposal will be upheld under
the U.S. Constitution.&quot;[36]

<p>

A two-tiered mediating proposal might offer a small, &quot;standard&quot;
educational tax credit of perhaps $500 to all parents of school-aged
children, and a larger tax credit of up to $3,000 for &quot;itemized&quot;
educational expenditures, broadly defined to include everything
from enrichment experiences for the public school student to private
school tuition to home school expenses. (As a general rule, tax
credits should be no higher than the average cost of local private
school tuition -- which is generally $2,500 to $3,000.[37] If keyed
to the average public school per-pupil expenditure -- as some
voucher plans propose -- the efficiency of the marketplace is
undermined by artificial inflation.)

<p>

This would limit the threat of regulation while expanding the
coalition of beneficiaries.[38]

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

<center>
<font size=+1><b><i>
Freedom is the air that true<br>
equality must breathe to<br>
survive.
</i></b></font>
</center>

<p><hr size=3 width=60% noshade><p>

Any proposal, however, must be considered in light of state constitutions.
Given the variance among state constitutions, as exemplified by
Idaho and Minnesota, educational choice proposals are probably
best handled at the state level. State action will be increasingly
viable as grass-roots sentiment mounts to eliminate the federal
role in education.

<p>

<center><h3>Conclusion</h3></center>

<p>

In <I>Perspectives on the Reagan Years</I>, political analyst
John Palmer argues that the Reagan Administration heightened public
awareness of an inevitable tension among political values that
decades of economic prosperity had obscured. Palmer refers to
the tensions among efficiency, social equity, and individual liberty
-- the reconciliation of which John Maynard Keynes identified
as &quot;the political problem of mankind.&quot; Just as education
was one component of the Great Society poverty programs, educational
choice was a key component of the Reagan Administration's efforts
to remake the welfare state in the image of its own philosophy.
The Reagan Administration argued that the American version of
the welfare state unduly sacrificed both individual liberty and
efficiency in the pursuit of social justice and that more diligent
concern for the former would inevitably promote the latter.

<p>

Reagan officials trumpeted educational choice as a means to mediate
between the competing values of liberty and equality -- a role
that could not have been claimed for choice without a substantial
redefinition of equality in the wake of Great Society failures.
In the words of former Secretary of Education Lauro Cavazos, appointed
by Reagan, &quot;[e]vidence shows that the growing demand for
parental choice in the United States derives not simply from a
desire for improved test scores, but from changing perspectives
on liberty and equity. It flows from an urgent reconsideration
of the role of the family and of other institutions and associations
that mediate between the individual and the State.&quot;[39]

<p>

Conservative advocates of choice must move quickly to popularize
a definition of social justice that reserves respect for individual
liberty and the primacy of the family. A more thorough attempt
at reconciling &quot;equality&quot; with &quot;liberty&quot; is
beyond the scope of the present paper. Suffice it to say that
the central issue is human dignity; that the phrase &quot;all
men are created equal&quot; promises no more -- and no less --
than equal moral worth, and that freedom is the air that true
equality must breathe to survive.

<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>-- by Jennifer A. Marshall, education policy analyst, and Jennifer
E. Marshall, welfare policy analyst.</i>

<p><hr><p>

