<html>
<head>
<title>Wanted: Activists</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<H2>8th Annual Conservative Leadership Conference promises biggest event ever in November
</H2></center>
<P>
<BR>
<dd>	Leadership Institute president Morton Blackwell's 22nd Law of the Public Policy Process cautions committed conservatives:  "Never miss a political meeting if there's the slightest chance you'll wish you'd been there."
<DD>	Take Morton's message to heart and you won't want to miss the eighth annual Conservative Leadership Conference, a spectacle which former U.S. Vice President Dan Quayle has credited with ". . .producing a new generation of conservative leaders." 
<DD>	The conference theme is "Conservative Grassroots: A Revolution Comes of Age." The event will be held November 21-23 in Washington, D.C.
<DD>	Morton said, "The Conservative Leadership Conference is unique, because it trains grass roots activists in the fundamentals of political technology.  
<DD>	"It's the only conference that gives activists the keys to victory in public policy battles."
<DD>	Since its founding, the conference has been directed by Morton; Reed Irvine, president of Accuracy in Academia; and Paul Weyrich, president of the Free Congress Foundation.
<DD>	It's three exciting and challenging days of grassroots training and networking you won't find anywhere else.  
<DD>	Moreover, expert speakers will give inside information on the upcoming elections and offer lessons on political effectiveness.
<DD>	Featured speakers of previous years include: elected officials such as longtime Institute supporters House Majority Leader Dick Armey and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,  Speaker Newt Gingrich, and Senator Paul Coverdell; stalwart activists Phyllis Schlafly and Ralph Reed; and conservative media figures such as columnist Tony Snow and satirist P.J. O'Rourke.
<DD>	Three-time attendee Cindy Gustafson reported, "The Conservative Leadership Conference combines all the best elements of a political meeting: the chance to meet activists and leaders from throughout the country, training in the latest political technology and presentations on the most important issues facing us today."
<DD>	"It's also the best deal that I have found," she said.
<P>
<DD><I>	The Eighth Annual Conservative Leadership Conference will be held November <DD>21-23 at the Metro Center Marriott in Washington, D.C. </I>
<P>
<DD>	Registration covers all conference sessions, materials, three receptions, a luncheon and two banquets for three days.  It's a bargain at only $169 before October 1st, and $189 thereafter.  
<DD>	Students can get a special reduced-rate registration of only $50, but it doesn't include meals.   However you register, this isn't a political meeting you can miss.  
<DD>	And don't wait too long to sign up: this year's registrations are already far ahead of last year's.  Reserve your place today at a savings-while there is still room. 
<P>
<BR>
<I>	Eric Putman is conference coordinator.  Call him to register or to recommend someone for the conference at (703)247-2000 or (800)827-5323.  
</I>
<P>
