<h2>April's Contents</h2>

<b>4/30/96</b>
<ul>
<li><a href="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/bg1078.html">Is There A "Clinton Crunch"?</a>: How the 1993 Budget Plan Affected the Economy...new from The Heritage Foundation.
<li>Are you familiar with the <a href="/pff/i-new.html">Summer Scholars Program</a> from the Progress & Freedom Foundation?
<li>A bill to promote adoption is introduced and a hearing is called on the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban in this week's <a href="/townhall/FRC/hotline/hotline.html">legislative hotline</a> from the Family Research Council.
<li>New columns from <a href="/wash_times/">The Washington Times National Weekly</a> target the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act veto:<ul>
<li>Pruden on Politics: The stern rebuke of a <a href="http://www.washtimes-weekly.com/wash_times/pruden.5_5.html">Sunday-school boy</a>.
<li>Suzanne Fields: Time for another <a href="http://www.washtimes-weekly.com/wash_times/fields.5_5.html">killer euphemism</a>?
</ul>
<li>Individuals who save get <a href="/savers/library/15.html">third-class treatment</a> under the ordinary income tax, according the Savers & Investors League.  Their newest <a href="/savers/library/advis53.html">Congressional advisory</a> says: It's time to terminate tax bias against savings.
</ul>



<b>4/29/96</b>
<ul>
<li>The May 6th issue of <i>National Review</i> headlines: <a href="/nationalreview/06may96/feature.html">Reagan's Spoiled Children</a>; malaise and infighting are threatening the future of the conservative movement.
<li>Have you seen Capital Research Center's newest newsletter? <i>Foundation Watch</i> monitors the activities of private foundations and analyzes their impact on <a href="/crc/fw/">American society</a>.
<li>"Americans are tired of our oppressive tax code and they want a new
               system. But to get there, they need an honest and open debate. They're
               not getting it from the politicians and the media." 
 says F.R. Duplantier in todays <a href="/townhall/columnists/dupl0429.html">Behind the Headlines</a>
<li>Did the Republicans derail their own Revolution? Paul Weyrich ponders this question in today's <a href="/townhall/columnists/weyrich/042996.html">Dateline Washington</a>
</ul>
<b>4/26/96</b>
<ul>
<LI>It's almost too bizarre to be believed, but reports of fetal cannibalism in
communist China have been confirmed. F.R. Duplantier goes <a href="/townhall/columnists/dupl0426.html">Behind the Headlines</a>
<li><a href="/townhall/columnists/weyrich/042596.html">Dateline Washington</a> explores the conflicts of the Whitewater Independent Council.
<li>When character goes AWOL,
everyone is endangered. Find out
more in Family Research Center's latest radio
<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/c96d26.html">commentary</a>. 
<li><a href="/townhall/FRC/fampol/fp96ded.html">With Liberty and Justice for All:
                                   Redefining the Educational
                                   Choice Debate</a> from the Family Research Council in now available.
<li>The Big Media, Are They Objective? Todays <a href="/townhall/infotain/humor/ccc/042696.html">Cartoon</a> doesn't think so.
<li><a href="/townhall/columnists/chav0424.html">Minimum Wage: Bad Idea GOP Fears to Fight</a> by columnist Linda Chavez
<li><a href="/townhall/columnists/rock0426.html">Hillary's Revenge</a> by columnist Llewellyn Rockwell.  Find out why Hillary is finally getting HER health care reform.

</ul>
<b>4/25/96</b>
<ul>
<li><a href="/townhall/columnists/fume0425.html">The Strangling Vines of Regulation</a> by Micheal Fumento
<li>Thousands of children will die in communist China's state-run orphanages this
year, and it won't be any accident." say F.R. Duplantier is his daily commentary <a href="/townhall/columnists/dupl0425.html">Behind the Headlines</a> 

<li><a href="/townhall/columnists/rock0424.html">Buchanan's Old Right Opposed Tarrifs</a> by Town Hall's new columnist Llewellyn Rockwell
<li>Today's <a href="/townhall/infotain/humor/ccc/042596.html">Cartoon</a> suggests Clinton makes Nixon look like an angel
<li>Have the Republicans Lost Their Vigor? Paul Weyrich says why in <a href="/townhall/columnists/weyrich/042496.html">Dateline Washington:</a>
<li><a href="/wash_times/campaign.4_28.html">Clinton Seeks to Please Gays</a> in the Washington Times Campaign '96 update.
</ul>
<p>
<b>4/24/96</b>
<ul>
<li>Should China's monstrous abuse of human rights affect our relationship with that country? <a href="/townhall/columnists/dupl0424.html">Rep. Smith on China</a> by F.R. Duplantier.
<li>Llewellyn Rockwell suggests: <a href="/townhall/columnists/rock0422.html">China: Trade Yes, Aid No</a>.
<li>Health care reform is on the front burner again. And everyone is talking about Medical Savings Accounts. Phyllis Schlafly says: <a href="/townhall/columnists/schl0418.html">MSAs are the Republicans' Best Issue</a>.
<li>According to several surveys, Americans disapprove of what they see on TV. But television executives insist that sex sells. <a href="/townhall/columnists/chav0417.html">Hollywood Misses American Reality</a>, counters Linda Chavez.
<li><i>Laughter is the best medicine</i>: Gary Bauer of the Family Research Council gives tribute to <a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/c96d24.html">Erma Bombeck</a> in his daily radio commentary.
</ul>
<b>4/23/96</b>
<ul>
<li>Town Hall welcomes <b>Llewellyn H. Rockwell</b>, president of the Ludwig von Mises Institute in Auburn, Alabama.
<ul>
<li>Rockwell discusses one of the oldest federal scandals in <a href="/townhall/columnists/rock0402.html">The Farm Trick Reform</a>.
<li>What Washington institution can make or break elections, bail out entire foreign governments, bankrupt whole industries, yet operates with less oversight than the CIA? Llewellyn Rockwell suggests that we <a href="/townhall/columnists/rock0409.html">End the Fed's Free Ride</a>. 
<li>Big government's biggest enemy is racing towards Washington: <a href="/townhall/columnists/rock0416.html">The Standard Bearer Returns</a>.
</ul>
<li><a href="/pff/">The Progress & Freedom Foundation</a> is holding a policy forum tomorrow on <i>The Meaning and Implications of the <a href="/townhall/events/welcome.html.cgi">Telecommunications Act</a></i>.
<li><b>Whitewater Update</b>: President Clinton is scheduled to give videotaped testimony on April 28; and it's expected to be a marathon session. Check out the details in this week's update from <a href="http://www.washtimes-weekly.com/wash_times/ww.4_28.html">The Washington Times National Weekly</a>.
<li>Bill Kristol predicts a Dole defeat against Clinton, and more in the <a href="/nationalreview/daily/nr042296.html">Washington Daily News</a>. 
<li>The communists in China may have nothing but contempt for the democratic values of the West, but that doesn't stop them from lusting after the prosperity that only a free society can attain...<a href="/townhall/columnists/dupl0423.html">Chinese Bandits</a> by F.R. Duplantier.
  
</ul>
<b>4/22/96</b>
<ul>
<li>The Constitutional amendment for a two-thirds supermajority to raise taxes lost in the House by just 37 votes. Get the update and other <a href="/townhall/FRC/hotline/hotline.html">legislative news</a> from the Family Research Council.
<li>The Senate Faces <a href="/heritage/library/categories/govern/bgup274.html">
Term Limits</a>.

<li>China reminds us that it's not to be trusted, in F.R. Duplantier's column <a href="/townhall/columnists/dupl0422.html">Taiwan</a>.
<li>From the May-June issue of <i>Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship</i>,
 <a href="/heritage/p_review/may96/norqu.html">The Spirit of '96</a> by Grover Norquist, president of <a href="/atr/1.html">Americans for Tax Reform</a>.
<li>Pete du Pont points out that good ideas don't always disappear, just because they are proposed by losing candidates.  As the flat tax resurfaces, this time by the Dole campaign, du Pont credits the <a href="/townhall/columnists/dupo0410.html">Forbes Legacy</a>.
<li>Though no one, as yet, has gotten sick, iced tea is banned from restaurants across the nation. Michael Fumento suggests that the <a href="/townhall/columnists/fume0417.html">Latest Scare is a Tempest in a Teapot</a>.  

</ul>
