<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
April 24, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Republicans Have Lost Their Vigor"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>

<P>These are dark days for the Republicans.<P>
<ul>
<LI> Speaker Newt Gingrich says his party is in a funk.
<LI> Former Cabinet Secretary Bill Bennett says that the campaign of GOP Presidential nominee Bob Dole is uninspiring and unfocused. Bennett suggests that Dole step down as Majority Leader. 
<LI> Liberal attacks on Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr have begun to take hold. The Democrats believe they can now blunt the effects of any convictions which might come out of the current Arkansas trial as well as any revelations from concurrent Senate hearings. 
<LI> Democrats in Congress unite to defeat any and all significant Republican initiatives on any legislation, leaving Bill Clinton in the driver's seat. 
<LI> The respected political analyst Charles Cook now says the Democrats have a one-in-three chance of recapturing the Congress, something which would have been unthinkable six months ago. 
<LI> Organized labor is spending huge sums of money targeting freshmen Republicans on the minimum wage through radio and TV commercials. No comparable spending is countering this from the Republican side.
<LI> Talk show host Rush Limbaugh, one of the most reliable parties supporting Republicans on the air, now says he may file for a trial separation from the Republican party because he doesn't want to be associated with people who are unwilling to stand up and fight for what they say they believe. 
<LI> All polls now show Bill Clinton leading Bob Dole by double digits. Polls also show Democrats in the lead for Congress. 
</UL>
<P>As I say, these are not happy times for Republicans. Rush Limbaugh is on to something. The problem here is not that the electorate has suddenly turned liberal. The problem is not that the so called mainstream media is more vicious than they were during the 1994 election season, for example. The problem is not that the liberals suddenly have a set of ideas which have captured the imaginations of the American people. The problem is not that times are so good that it is inevitable that the incumbent President will win. 
<P>The problem is simply this: The Republicans have lost all passion for their beliefs. A year ago, as they worked through the Contract with America, Republicans fought for their ideas with great conviction and the public was with them. They did so, it turns out, because they were dead certain that Bill Clinton would collapse from the momentum they had started. Republicans had but one battle plan: force Clinton to surrender, then declare victory and go on to the next triumph. 
<P>But Bill Clinton did not surrender. In fact, Bill Clinton rallied his troops. There seems to be a lot of passion left in those who believe in big government. The Republicans collapsed, not Bill Clinton. The Republicans began to compromise and compromise and compromise. The more they gave in, the more the Democrats united in the Senate to stop Republican initiatives. The more the initiatives died, the less the Republicans wanted to continue fighting for them. Now all the intensity is on the side of the Democrats who smell the chance to come back to power in a major way. 
<P>Republicans, meanwhile, are paying lip service to a host of good ideas in which they once insisted they really believed. These range from term limits to cutting out harmful federal programs to medical savings accounts. The problem is that there is no passion behind their rhetoric. They give their supporters little to get excited over. Compare what is happening today to the fight the Republicans waged against Bill and Hillary's health care plan in the 103rd Congress. The intensity back then was all with the Republicans. 
<P>So what happened? What happened is simply this. The mainstream media attacked the Republicans vigorously. Some among their ranks couldn't take the heat. They urged compromise. Republican leaders tried to appease this group through compromise. Democrats, upon hearing of proposed compromises, sensed weakness and decided to go for the jugular. 
<P>Then came the 1995 off-year elections. Republicans lost them. Fear and panic swept their ranks. They offered more compromise, emboldening the Democrats, who managed to get themselves together after having been badly split last year. Republicans, then, all but threw in the towel on a variety of issues, demoralizing their own troops. This, combined with a bruising Republican primary season where all the passion and excitement was with the losing candidates for President, brought us to where we are today. 
<P>Limbaugh is essentially correct. If the Republicans don't want to go all out to fight for their ideas, if they don't want to stand up and defend themselves, and if they don't want to be on the offensive instead of the defensive, then they do not deserve the blind loyalty of Limbaugh or anyone else. Defeat is not inevitable. But as any good coach knows, to win on the playing field you have to believe in your own team. If the Republicans don't believe in their own ideas enough to fight for them, then they shouldn't be surprised when people who believe in contrary ideas, no matter how wrong they may be, end up trouncing them for good. 
<P>If the Republicans keep going where they are going, they will give Limbaugh one more chance to say, "See, I told you so." 
<P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
<center>
<P>
