<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 21, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Doles Bold Move"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>


<P>
<P>
<P>
"Doles Bold Move"
<P>
I thought I would wait until the dust settled a bit before commenting on Senate Majority Leader Bob Doles gamble to resign and run without office for the Presidency. That I was surprised by this development is an understatement. That Sheila Burke was not one of the five people in the world who knew several weeks ahead of time that Dole was going to do this, is the best element of all. It demonstrated that at last Dole had shed his emotional dependence on Burke, which is a positive development. <P>
Dole demonstrated that it is possible to teach an old political dog new tricks. Most of us who thought we knew him well did not believe he had it in him to pull this off. After all, even if he lost the Presidency, Dole still would have been the Republican Leader. Although there was brave talk about running someone against him, when it came to the moment of truth, he probably would have remained Republican Leader for another two years. <P>
The Dole move probably means that Senate Majority Whip Trent Lott becomes Majority Leader. He will likely prove to be a far more energetic and able Leader than Dole and that has boosted the morale of the Republican Senators. So giving all of this up to go after the big prize indeed was a stunning development, at least in Washington. In the rest of the nation, it was not greeted as such a remarkable event because the rest of the nation is sensibly not as caught up in politics as Washington. <P>
The Dole move did have an effect on his campaign. It gave his troops new hope that he could win, which is something he badly needed to do. It afforded him a new opportunity to redefine himself. Up to now, to the extent that anyone knew anything about Bob Dole, it was that he was the consummate Washington Insider, not exactly a compliment these days. The Dole move represents a break with the past, even though stunned Democrats bitterly complain that Dole cant shed 36 years of Congressional service just like that. <P>
Now comes the hard part. Without the advantages that being Senate Majority Leader gave him to generate headlines, Dole must distinguish himself boldly from President Bill Clinton. Can Dole, who supports Clinton on Bosnia and China really distinguish himself from Clinton on foreign policy? Can Dole, who is no stranger to tax increases, really be credible in calling for a tax rate reduction? Can Dole, who voted for almost all of Bill Clintons judicial appointments, really come down hard on the sort of judges Bill Clinton has appointed? <P>
The Dole camp has maintained that this election would be about character and integrity. Unfortunately for Dole, all of the latest polls show that the public, by a large margin, actually believes Bill Clinton is more honest and has greater integrity than Bob Dole. That is probably the most remarkable development of this campaign. If someone like Bill Clinton, who has made a career out of dissembling, can sell honesty and integrity to the American public, Bob Dole had better hope that he can distinguish himself from Clinton on issues.<P>
Clinton is not helping Dole in any way. Dole was about to deliver a speech on welfare reform and the Clinton folks heard about it. Clinton rushed to embrace the welfare reform model proposed by Wisconsin Republican Governor Tommy Thompson. Republican Governors were outraged, but Bill Clinton got on the scoreboard first. <P>
A  Washington Times cartoon showed Clinton in the form of a parrot in a cage next to a radio. On the radio was news of Doles impending speech on welfare reform. The Clinton-like parrot squawked "Welfare reform. Bawk. Welfare reform." That is about the size of it but Clinton has done it well. <P>
The truth is that the Republican Congress sent the President two versions of welfare reform, both of which he had praised at one point. Clinton vetoed both. <P>
Therein lies the one hook that Dole has on Clinton and one which could prove to be decisive in this campaign. The President says one thing and does the opposite. Voters may think they trust Bill Clinton right now. They may think he agrees with them on the issues. But if Dole can pound home the truth that Bill Clinton is, in a sea of Washington hypocrisy, the biggest fish of them all, then Dole may actually have an effective weapon against the President. <P>
Voters, at the end of the day, dislike hypocrisy more than anything else. It remains to be seen if Dole can be bold enough, after this very bold restart to his campaign, to carry that issue to the finish line. <P>


<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
