<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 15, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"We Are Winning"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>

<P><center>
by Rep. Mark Neumann (R-WI)
</center>
<P>
<P>In 1995, I came to Congress along with 72 other newly elected freshman Members.  
<P>Before any of us even took our oath of office, we resolved ourselves to achieving a very specific goal  to reduce the federal deficit, to balance our budget and to eliminate wasteful Washington spending.  	
<P>Now, just 16 months later, I have good news to report: we are winning this battle!
<P>It hasnt been easy, I can assure you of that.  But the results we have achieved, are well worth the effort.
<P>Let me show you the financial picture of our nation, when I came here, and where we stand now. 
<P>When we arrived here a year ago, this is what we found:  The red line on this chart illustrates the problem of the federal deficit.  It was at about $200 billion per year and growing indefinitely.
<P>If we had allowed this trend to continue, our country would sink further and further into debt, creating a disastrous future for our children and grandchildren.  But we did not allow that to happen.  We took action.
<P>First, we passed a recessions bill.  That means that right off the bat, we took $11 billion of wasteful spending out of the budget.
<P>Then the appropriators went to work.  John Kasich, the chairman of the Budget Committee, set a goal and said $23 billion of wasteful spending had to be eliminated. "Come in $23 billion under the previous year, or our plan to balance the budget wont work," Kasich told them.
<P>Folks, this is the first time in a generation this has been done. 
<P>By December, this is where we were.  We were making progress, but still, we dared to dream.  We dared to dream that we could restore a better future for this Nation.  We dared to dream that we could get our country back on track.
<P>If you look at this chart, you see that this green line is the path to a balanced budget, and the road to a secure financial future for our children and grandchildren.
<P>So we set a deficit target for fiscal year 1996.  That target was $157 billion.  So what happened?  The financial markets looked at this and they reacted positively, and exactly as predicted.
<P>The most positive and helpful sign for the American people was that interest rates stayed down.  And when that happened, more people  especially younger folks  could afford to buy houses and cars.
<P>This created jobs and job opportunities for our young people because somebody has to build those houses and cars.
<P>Folks, this is exactly how America is supposed to work.
<P>What followed next was our unemployment rate went down, as did the welfare rolls and interest cost to the government.
<P>But that was not the end of the story.  When the markets reacted in a positive way, and the appropriators fulfilled their commitment to our Nation, not only did we hit our target for a balanced budget, we came in $8 billion less than where we needed to be in order to reach a balanced budget in 2002.
<P>That is the story behind the story. We are $8 billion ahead of where we need to be in order to reach a balanced budget by the year 2002!
<P>This is great news, and Im happy to deliver it to you, because its not often that you hear good news out of Washington.
<P>And theres even more good news.  Were on track to balancing the budget without raising your taxes.  We did not go back to the 1993 way of raising your taxes.  Weve accomplished this by truly shrinking parts of this government.
<P>This Congress has kept its commitment to balancing the budget.  In the past, other Congresses have spent money hand over fist thinking that was the way to win over the voters.
<P>But this Congress understands that the best thing we can do right now for the American worker, and for our children and our grandchildren is to balance the budget.
<P>A balanced federal budget is a permanent solution to our Nations economic problems.  Never again should we give in to quick-fix gimmicks, election year charades, and snake-oil solutions.<P>
What does a balanced federal budget mean to you and your family?  It means:<P>
<ul><li>lower interest rates which makes it easier to buy houses, cars and other goods;
<LI>it means lower taxes;
<li>it means more jobs, lower unemployment, and fewer people on the welfare rolls;
<li>and finally it means higher salaries and more take-home pay to spend as you see fit.
</ul>Folks, we are winning! Is there more to be done?  Sure there is.<P>
But with your help, we can cut through the demagoguery of the other side and keep our focus on balancing the budget.  When we do that, we will return economic security to you, and a brighter financial future to your children.<P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
