http://www.conservative.org:80/townhall/columnists/weyrich/051496.html 204.71.237.88 19970208181348 text/html 5686
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 08-Feb-97 18:14:35 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 03-Jun-96 13:37:53 GMT
Content-length: 5501
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 14, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"A New Scenario for Dole"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>

<P>
"A New Scenario for Dole"
<P>
Right now things are pretty grim in the Dole camp. As former Vice President Dan Quayle suggested yesterday, things will probably get worse before they get better because Dole is out of money. Moreover, because Bill Clinton was unchallenged in the primaries, he has millions to spend. Dole, on the other hand, remains mired in the muck of Senate procedures where the likes of Ted Kennedy can get the best of him.<P>
There is an alternative scenario kicking around which, if Dole can pull it off, would transform his campaign overnight. You will recall that the Balanced Budget Constitutional Amendment failed by a single vote in the U.S. Senate last year. It received the two-thirds majority needed in the House with votes to spare. But six Democrats who had previously voted for such an amendment suddenly switched positions and the Amendment went down to defeat. When that happened the whole push for the "Contract With America" went into the tank.<P>
The reason that some of the Democrats claimed they switched was articulated by Senator Byron Dorgan of North Dakota in two words: Social Security. Because the so called Social Security Trust Fund is considered on budget, the surpluses it presently produces are used to offset other government spending. Dorgan insisted that this does not offer enough protection for Social Security. In fact, Dorgan came off as some sort of hero in North Dakota because voters believed he had helped to save Social Security.<P>
Well, Republicans ought to just accept that argument. Taking Social Security off budget would mean that to achieve a balanced budget another $35 billion per year would have to be cut from domestic spending. Sounds good to me. Maybe we finally could eliminate the Legal Services Corporation, the National Endowment for the Arts, Goals 2000, Americorps, and other such programs which produce more harm than good.<P>
Right now, quietly behind the scenes, Dole and Illinois Democratic Senator Paul Simon, who fervently believes in a balanced budget and who would like to cap his Senate career by seeing such an amendment passed, are trying to see if the votes are there to pass a new version of the Amendment which takes Social Security off budget.<P>
It is hard to believe that Democrats would provide Dole with such an opportunity. However, the two North Dakota Senators, especially, were so high profile in their contention that they really did favor a balanced budget. If the Amendment got Social Security off the books, it may be hard for them to back away from the issue now.<P>
This new version of the Balanced Budget Amendment should be able to easily pass the House. And guess what? A Constitutional Amendment does not go to Bill Clinton for his signature. It goes directly to the states for ratification.<P>
Picture this:  there are now 31 Republican Governors and half of the state legislative houses are controlled by the Republicans. Imagine that Presidential candidate Bob Dole, now lacking money to run a regular campaign, would go from state to state urging the legislatures to ratify the Balanced Budget Amendment. It would highlight the fact that he was able to get such an amendment through the Congress; it would give the Republican Governors and legislatures a chance to showcase positive changes they are making in state government; and Dole addressing state legislatures would probably get live coverage in most of the states where it would take place.<P>
The Dole campaign, which is on the rocks in every way right now, could be transformed overnight into a positive force for an initiative which is supported overwhelmingly by the American people. There is little that Bill Clinton could do about it. Clinton opposed the Constitutional Amendment for a Balanced Budget when it was before the Congress. His liberal allies know that if such an amendment is in place, federal funding for many of their favorite programs becomes dubious at best.<P>
This scenario is probably too good to be true. My guess is that if Dole and Simon do come up with a Balanced Budget Amendment that satisfies the two Senators from North Dakota, a couple of other Democrats who had previously voted for the Amendment will switch to be against it on the grounds that removing Social Security from the budget will require cutting too much from domestic spending.<P>
As Peter Ferrara suggests in a column in today's Washington Times, Dole should then be commended for trying. In the off chance Dole would be able to make it happen, all bets would be off on the Presidential race. The chance to hammer home the fact that Dole favors a Balanced Budget Amendment and Bill Clinton does not, and make that case before state legislatures in very real and graphic terms, live and in person, would turn around the dour prospects for a Dole presidency.<P>


<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
