HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 08-Feb-97 18:15:45 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 03-Jun-96 13:37:52 GMT
Content-length: 5519
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 7, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"FDA Commissioners Arrogance"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>


<P>
I have spoken before of the arrogance of the federal Food and Drug Administration, the FDA, in its constant effort to seize more power for itself. Further evidence of that arrogance just keeps on building. <P>
The Washington Legal Foundation has filed a First Amendment lawsuit against the FDA, challenging the agencys crackdown on the dissemination of information regarding the "off label" uses of FDA approved drugs and medical devices. The Washington Legal Foundation lawsuit contends that the FDAs restrictions violate the First Amendment rights of both the providers and the recipients of such information. <P>
Federal law currently prohibits the manufacturer of an FDA approved drug or device from specifying on the product label any uses of the product other than the precise use approved by the FDA. However, doctors are free to prescribe FDA approved products for uses other than those specified by the product label. In fact, in many areas of medicine, most of the treatment recognized by the medical community consists of off label uses of FDA approved products. <P>
Recently the FDA has begun a crackdown on manufacturers who become involved, in any way, in the dissemination of information about the off label uses of their own products, such as distributing to doctors medical text books which contain information about the off label drug uses. The Washington Legal Foundation suit contends that this is a violation of the First Amendment which effects not only the producer of the product but also the recipients, first the doctor and ultimately the patient. <P>
Commissioner David Kessler of the FDA refused to appear at a scheduled deposition on April 24th. The legal foundation is trying to depose Kessler in order to, in its words, "establish that he was personally responsible for the FDA crackdown and that in directing the FDA to implement its no policy, he gave no thought to whether the crackdown might violate free speech rights." Washington Legal Foundations lawyers claim that senior FDA officials deposed to date in the lawsuit have admitted that First Amendment concerns played no role in their policy deliberations. The foundation contends that it needs to depose Kessler as well to establish that he too was oblivious to First Amendment rights in formulating agency policy.<P>
Well, Kessler was a no-show. Instead he filed a motion to quash the deposition which Federal Judge Royce Lamberth will rule on shortly. Such a move on Kesslers part is unprecedented. "It is outrageous that Commissioner Kessler thinks he is above the law and not subject to the same litigation rules as anyone else who gets involved in a lawsuit," said the Foundations Chief Legal Counsel Richard Samp. Samp pointed out that even Bill Clinton has had to give a deposition in connection with Whitewater and the First Lady has had to appear before a grand jury in connection with the White House travel office. <P>
Samp contends that Kessler said one of his top priorities as Commissioner would be to crackdown on the off label uses of FDA approved products. Never mind that people are being cured by these products. Never mind that such products are recognized as the only possible remedy in some medical cases. What the FDA seeks is total control. <P>
That attitude was reflected in a very personal letter former Congresswoman Marilyn Lloyd  sent to some Members of the House. The Congresswoman from Tennessee served in the House for 20 years before retiring after the 1994 elections. Marilyn Lloyd told her former colleagues that she had undergone a mastectomy in 1991 and had chosen silicone breast implant surgery. But just before her surgery was to take place the FDA ruled that such operations could not go forward. <P>
Mrs. Lloyd contends that the FDA made this ruling with no scientific evidence that such implants were harmful. She quotes Dr. John E. Woods, vice chairman of the Department of Surgery at the Mayo Clinic as saying, "Instead of protecting the health and concerns of women, this moratorium caused undue stress and anxiety for women with implants and women who wanted them around the world." Mrs. Lloyd told the Members of Congress to whom she wrote, "I want you to understand that the irresponsible nature of the FDAs decision has led to real women  mothers, wives and daughters  dying needlessly." <P>
Again the issue here is one of control. That is what David Kessler and his agents are all about. Control over other peoples lives. <P>
There is more and more evidence that the FDA is a government agency totally out of control. This Congress owes it to the long-suffering American public to take the steps necessary to tie Commissioner Kesslers hands.  Congress must do this before more innocent people die needlessly because they are unsuspectingly caught up in one of Kesslers little power games. <P>



<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
