<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 3, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"The Real Solution to Illegal Immigration"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>

<P>
"The Real Solution to Illegal Immigration"
<P>
The Senate has passed an immigration bill by a 97 to 3 margin. The bill is similar to a measure which has already passed the House. President Clinton is signaling that he will sign the bill. So our worries about immigration are over, right?<P>
Sorry, but I've heard this one before. In 1986, the same Senator Alan Simpson of Wyoming who guided this bill through the Senate, assured us that immigration was going to be under control because employers would be required to verify that a prospective employee was in the country legally. The measure didn't work. It did, however, increase the number of illegal documents in circulation.<P> 
This bill does contain some provisions which have merit. The bill doubles the number of officers on boarder patrol. It also provides for enforcement of the measure, which has been on the books since 1882, regarding legal immigrants. A sponsor is supposed to guarantee that the person he brings to this country will not be on the public assistance rolls for five years after coming here. Since the 1960's that provision has never been enforced. A combination of court decisions and lenient administrations have caused the law to be ignored. This bill gives that measure some teeth if an Administration has the courage to use it.
<P>The legislation also contains a provision for a pilot program to create new documents that would be difficult to copy.  However, one of the bill's chief sponsors, Sen. Charles Grassley (R-Iowa), was unable to answer how such a law would keep the new documents out of the hands of those who misrepresent themselves to authorities.
<P> All of this aside, this bill is utterly meaningless without true welfare reform. Welfare reform has been twice vetoed by this President. The reason some immigrants come here is to work. Fine. If they are taking jobs Americans won't fill, I don't have a problem with that. But many illegal immigrants come here for our welfare benefits. Unless, and until, it is clear that we as a society can deny welfare benefits to anyone who is not here legally, no beefed up boarder patrols or document controls are going to mean very much. 
<P>Pass genuine welfare reform and watch the flow of illegal immigrants dry up to manageable proportions. Don't pass welfare reform and watch this bill fail the way the immigration reform bill of 1986 failed. It is almost that simple. 
<P>


<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
