<head><title>For the Record -- NR</title></head>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2>For the Record</H2></CENTER>
<HR>
06-November-1995

<P> 

 
 
<p><li>Politicians mostly circumspect concerning <b>O. J. Simpson's</b> acquittal. Only<b> Pat Buchanan</b> condemned 
verdict. President<b> Bill Clinton</b> issued a statement: ``Our system of justice requires respect for the decision. 
At this moment, our thoughts and prayers should be with the families of the victims of this terrible crime.'' 
<b>Bob Dole's</b> statement told Americans: ``It is very important at this time that we use all our energies to find 
ways to understand each other and bring us together.''<b> Phil Gramm</b> deemed it inappropriate ``for a member 
of the Senate to be commenting on jury trials.'' <b>Colin Powell</b> said that the trial showed that the judicial 
system works and called on the country ``to move on.'' Also for moving on:<b> Lamar Alexander, Jack Kemp.</b> 
Gov. <b>Pete Wilson</b> said he ``would urge the removal of cameras from our courtrooms.''<b> Jesse Jackson</b> urged 
Simpson to lead the fight against domestic violence. . . . Even editorialists declined to judge the jury. New 
York Times faulted the police, prosecution, and Judge<b> Lance Ito</b> for ``bungling,'' and the defense for making 
``a prejudicial appeal,'' but took no position on the verdict. Not going out on a limb: the Washington Post, 
which noted that the acquittal ``stunned and disappointed'' some people but ``satisfied'' others. . . . Coverage 
of O.J. and racial division by the media fueled more talk about Powell. <b>Charles Krauthammer</b> argues that 
though a President Powell would prevent major reform of the welfare state, he would improve race 
relations. 
 
<p><li>White House is in an upbeat mood, buoyed by rising poll ratings and convinced that Republicans will field 
weak candidate next year. Clinton's strategy, which advisor<b> Dick Morris</b> calls ``triangulation,'' seeks to 
position him as a centrist, between congressional Republicans and Democrats.<b> Ann Devroy</b> (Washington 
Post) writes, ``Clinton's message that he is for the popular things Republicans favor -- like a balanced 
budget -- but against the unpopular things they propose -- like cutting Medicare -- is beginning to take.'' . . . 
Not all Democrats enthusiastic about the new strategy. Asked on Meet the Press to choose between Dole 
and Clinton, Sen.<b> Daniel Patrick Moynihan</b> (D., N.Y.) responded, ``I would rather have as President 
someone not running for the Presidency.'' Moynihan has clashed with White House recently over welfare 
and his proposal to save billions by reducing estimates of inflation. . . . Vice President<b> Al Gore</b> calls 
Republicans ``extremists,'' Clinton accuses them of raising taxes (actually Medicare deductibles, college-
loan fees, etc.) on the needy. Attacks led Newt Gingrich and Bob Dole to call off budget talks for now -- 
though Dole jokes that Gore's ``extremist'' talk ``may help me in some of the early primaries.'' . . . More 
tough budget talk from both sides: Clinton declares, ``I would gladly, gladly terminate my tenure here if the 
price of continuing it was just shelving everything I believe in about this country.'' Gramm says, ``He can 
hold us in session until the Second Coming and there is no possibility that I am ever going to spend one 
nickel above the level . . . in our budget.'' 
 
<p><li>Republican presidential candidates hold forum in New Hampshire. Comments Washington Post editorial: 
``Judging from what was said . . . the ideal President is someone who: 1) never had anything to do with the 
Federal Government in Washington, D.C.; 2) never set foot in Washington; 3) never even met someone who 
set foot in Washington; 4) never even voted to send someone else to Washington; 5) and wouldn't, if 
elected, even move to Washington.'' Alexander repeated call to ``cut their pay and send them home,'' Dole 
deflected questions about his age with good humor, </b>Bob Dornan</b> praised all the other candidates, Gramm 
softened his image by talking about his humble beginnings and his marriage. Focusing on tax reform were 
<b>Steve Forbes, Richard Lugar,</b> and<b> Arlen Specter</b>, while<b> Alan Keyes</b> continued to stress primacy of moral 
issues. . . . Pete Wilson's departure from presidential race leads to Dole endorsements by conservative Calif. 
Attorney General<b> Dan Lungren</b>, Calif. ex-Gov.<b> George Deukmejian</b>, and ex-co-chairman of RNC<b> Jeanie 
Austin</b>. 
 
<p><li>Gramm, seeking Cuban-American support, opposes Dole on English language, demands that<b> Fidel Castro</b> 
be barred from attending UN's fiftieth anniversary next month: ``The only purpose that we should allow 
Fidel Castro into America for is to put him in prison or to hang him. And frankly, I believe the people of 
Cuba should have first right to exercise either or both of those options.'' . . . Campaign memo by Gramm 
pollster<b> Linda DiVall</b>, leaked to press, summarizes focus-group results: ``Knowledge void on Gramm is still 
immense. . . Women were totally confused on his position on affirmative action and abortion.'' (He's against 
both.) . . . Buchanan warns that if Powell ``became the nominee and tried to make us a pro-abortion, pro-
gun-control, pro-affirmative-action party which celebrated New Deal and Great Society programs, then 
there will be an explosion in San Diego [convention] and I would fight him with everything I had.'' . . . It 
now looks unlikely that Perot's party will get on Calif. ballot. 
 
<p><li>Wall Street Journal quotes salon owner<b> Jordan Ferraro</b> on why more women are dyeing their hair red: ``I 
equate this with the fact that the Cold War has ended. The phrase, `Better dead than Red' has passed from 
our consciousness. . . . We're allowed now emotionally to become red.'' 

