<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What You Pay for Gas</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<blockquote>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>Thirty Taxes on Bread</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>By Peter J. Ferrara<BR>
<hr>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
 After you finally completed your income tax return last April
and mailed it off, you may have worked up quite an appetite. 
So you may have driven to the grocery store to buy a loaf of bread
to make a sandwich.  What you probably didn't realize was how
much you were <a href="/atr/tax-presentation/bredoped.html">paying in taxes again</a> when you bought the bread.
<P>
 In fact, in the process of production from the farm to the store,
the government imposes about 30 taxes on a loaf of bread.
<P>
 These include Federal income taxes, state income taxes, state
and local property taxes, federal payroll taxes, sales taxes,
capital gains taxes, unemployment compensation taxes, workmen's
compensation taxes, retailers' excise taxes, business license
taxes and fees, utility taxes, and state wheat farmer checkoff
taxes.
<P>
 For delivery trucks, farmers and bakers must pay a 12% manufacturers'
excise tax on the trucks, as well as a 15%-20% excise tax on the
tires.  They must also pay Federal gasoline taxes, including a
Federal diesel fuel excise tax of 20 cents per gallon, as well
as state gas taxes, truck highway use taxes, oil disposal fees,
environmental impact taxes, highway tolls, public highway user
taxes, personal property taxes on the vehicles, and taxes on auto
batteries.
<P>
 Finally, the phone in the bakery or on the farm is subject to
a 3% federal tax on general telephone services and another 3%
tax on long distance.  Many states also add additional taxes on
telephones averaging another 2%.
<P>
 A recent study by Price Waterhouse found that these taxes accounted
for 27.2% of the price of a loaf of bread, not counting sales
taxes paid by the consumer.  That means that almost 30% of what
you pay for bread, and more in some states due to the sales tax,
goes to the government in taxes rather than for the bread.  So
out of the average price for a loaf of bread of $1.09 in 1995,
about 30 cents went for taxes, plus another 5 cents on average
for sales taxes.  Everything that goes into making, marketing
and distributing the bread is paid for by the 70% or less of the
sales price, or about 79 cents, that remains after taxes are paid.
<P>
 These taxes are unfair to workers.  In a democracy, taxes should
not be hidden in the prices of products people buy.  They should
be explicit and clear, so that voters can determine whether they
think those taxes are worth what they are getting from their government.
<P>
 Thomas Jefferson wrote, &quot;Government should not take out
of the mouth of labor the bread that it has earned.&quot;  But
that is exactly what our greedy and overreaching government does
today.  It taxes you on your income when you earn it, and taxes
it again when you spend it, and taxes you over and over again
along the way.  As a result, the average family today actually
pays more in taxes than on food, clothing, and shelter combined.
<P>
 Tax relief for working people is long overdue.  Such tax reduction
would give workers more control over their own incomes and economic
future.  A major tax reduction would also greatly stimulate the
economy, leading to more jobs, higher wages, and expanded economic
opportunity and prosperity.
<P>
<hr>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2> Peter Ferrara is general counsel and chief
economist at Americans for Tax Reform</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>1320 18<SUP>th</SUP> Street N.W., Washington,
DC  20036  (202) 785-0266.</FONT></CENTER>
</blockquote>
</BODY>
</HTML>
